@NODE "Mail_296" "Re: Printing a RastPort (URGENT)"
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Fri, 12 Nov 1999 13:31:31 -0000
Subject: Re: Printing a RastPort (URGENT)
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: cd3b7edf40ec76fb9ff1bb5a3af88445

Hi Nick

> As promised I have attached the C code and I need it converted to
> blitz, I'm in a hurry so I will detail this better around 11:00AM GMT!
>  (I'm in a rush!)  

You must've been in a hurry, it was a Word(worth?) document or 
something.

> So can anybody convert this code to (working!) Blitz code, sorry it's
> in a mess!

I didn't read all of the code, but if the only problems you are 
having is because of Blitz's apparent non-support of unions then you 
are OK - cos it does support them.

There was a slight error in the amigalibs.res when it got converted, 
all the unions were screwed up.

However, if you want to do one, you'll just have to create a new 
newtype for it and use that.

For example, if I had this in C:

struct blah
{
    union
    {
        ULONG length;
        struct
        {
            WORD x;
            WORD y;
        } xy;
    }
};

Then in Blitz it would look something like:

NEWTYPE.anon1
    x.w
    y.w
END NEWTYPE

NEWTYPE.blah
    length.l[0]
    xy.anon1
END NEWTYPE

The [0] on the end of length tells Blitz that it doesn't take up any 
space in the NEWTYPE but you still access it as \length, not 
\length[0]. Because it takes up no space, it will share the same 
memory location the xy variable.

You just need to make sure that everything in the union has a [0] on 
the end except the last thing (which you should put after all the 
items with [0] for that union) which you need to let have some space, 
for the union to be stored in.


-- 
|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| © |\/| ][ |\| |\|   |   dave@satanicdreams.com
